The National Industrial Court in Port Harcourt, Rivers State, has granted an interim injunction stopping the proposed strike by civil servants. The workers had vowed to begin a warning strike on today following some unresolved issues involving the new minimum wage. Justice Z. M. Bashir, however, ordered that the organised labour, under Beatrice Itubo (Chairman, Nigeria Labour Congress -NLC); Austin Jonah (Trade Union Congress – TUC) and the Joint Rivers Negotiating Council, from proceeding on the strike. The order said: “The National Industrial Court, Port Harcourt, has granted an order of interim injunction restraining the defendants, either by themselves or through their servants, agents, privies, officers or otherwise howsoever called, from embarking on a strike on March 23, or any other day thereafter, pending the hearing and determination of the substantive motion on notice filed in this suit. “The trial court also granted an order of interim injunction restraining the defendants from interfering with the provision of services and other works by their members in the civil service of Rivers State pending the hearing and determination of the substantive motion on notice filed in this suit.”